# Regression Guardrails (Backend + Frontend)

When changing request/response fields, validators, SQL update logic, or refactoring service methods, follow this checklist before finishing.

## 1) Field Mapping Integrity (mandatory)
- If a field exists in create flow, verify update flow also maps it (and vice versa when expected).
- Keep field names aligned across: frontend payload, validator schema, controller, service update builder, DB columns, and response formatter.
- During refactors, do not remove existing update mappings unless a migration/design note explicitly says so.

## 2) Dynamic SQL Update Safety
- For dynamic `updateFields` builders, verify every editable form field has a corresponding `updateFields.push(...)`.
- If API returns success on update, verify meaningful persistence (not just request accepted).
- Prefer reading back updated row after UPDATE and returning that object.

## 3) Refactor Change Audit
- For touched service files, compare old vs new behavior for create, update, and format methods.
- If capping/status/ID logic is changed, run a targeted audit for unrelated fields (e.g., payout, approval %, notes).
- Use git diff/history to confirm no accidental field-drop regression.

## 4) Minimum Verification Before Completion
- Run lints for edited files.
- Run at least one real update-path verification (API or test) for the changed fields.
- If verification is skipped, explicitly state what remains unverified and why.

## 5) Response Discipline
- Do not claim "fixed" until persistence is validated.
- Mention restart requirement when runtime uses stale server process.

## 6) Conversion Postback Policy (strict)
- Fire publisher postback URL only when conversion status is exactly `approved`.
- For any non-approved status (including `pending`, `rejected`, `failed`, `hold`, `cancelled`, `rejected_cap`, `click_expired`), do not fire publisher postback.
- If conversion status changes from non-approved to `approved`, postback may be fired once according to idempotency safeguards.
